We would like to model the effect of various factors on miles per gallon. Lets start with a simple model where horsepower is the only predictor:

We built two versions of the model. The first is linear, the second is second-order polynomialboth using hp as the only predictor.

Lets make a plot:

## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

Which model is the best fit? Lets look at the root mean-sq of error:

## [1] 13.98982
## [1] 8.582239

Here we are fitting a curved line using natural splines with a 3rd order polynomial function

ggplot(data = mtcars, aes(x=hp, y=mpg)) +
  geom_smooth(method="lm", formula=y ~ poly(x, 3))

# If not want to use polynomial functions
library(splines)
ggplot(data = mtcars, aes(x=hp, y=mpg)) +
  geom_smooth(method="lm", formula=y ~ ns(x, 3))
